%S A395970 1,4,6,15,35,55,91,119,187,209,247,253,299,377,403,527,589,629,697,
%T A395970 731,817,893,989,1007,1121,1219,1357,1403,1541,1633,1679,2117,2263,
%U A395970 2291,2407,2573,2581,2759,2813,2929,2987,3103,3161,3379,3503,3937,4061,4247,4847,5069
%N A395970 Lexicographically earliest sequence of non-prime terms such that a(n) shares a factor with exactly n other terms.
%C A395970 If the sequence were to allow prime terms then one can show that a lexicographically earliest sequence would then not exist as one can start with k primes followed by all semiprimes such that the criteria of a(n) sharing a factor with exactly n other terms can be satisfied. A lexicographically earlier sequence could then always be created by increasing k. See the attached file.
%C A395970 There appears to be no easy method of generating each a(n) other than choosing the earliest semiprime that satisfies the condition that it can share with n other terms while not violating the same criteria for all other terms it may share a factor with. To achieve this when a prime appears as a factor for the first time one must track the number of subsequent terms that must contain that as a factor so that a(n) can be satisfied. Each time that prime appears as a factor in subsequent terms that number is decremented; when it reaches zero no further terms can contain that prime as a factor. When a candidate semiprime is considered one must calculate the number of required terms still to come that must contain its primes as factors, and add to that the number of terms that have already appeared that contain these primes as factors. If that sum equals n then that implies the candidate semiprime can be satisfied so it can be chosen as the next term. Typically the sum will be less than n, implying that the primes for the candidate will not be able to be chosen as factors of subsequent terms before the candidate term has shared with n other terms. In this case the next lowest semiprime candidate must then be trialled. For the terms studied it appears this method never allows the square of primes to be terms, and it conjectured this is true for all n>1.
%C A395970 The author thanks _N. J. A. Sloane_ for useful discussions.
%H A395970 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A395970/b395970.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A395970 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A395970/a395970_2.txt">Example of a lexicographically earlier sequence starting with primes</a>.
%e A395970 a(0) = 1, as 1 shares zero factors with any other terms.
%e A395970 a(1) = 4, the first non-prime term. As this is even there can only be one more even term.
%e A395970 a(2) = 6. This shares a factor with a(1) = 4, and so satisfies a(1) sharing a factor with one other term. This is the last even term.
%e A395970 a(3) = 15. This satisfies a(2) sharing a factor with two other terms; it is the last term divisible by 3. A smaller non-prime odd value is 9 = 3*3, but then a(2) would share factors with two terms so no further terms could contain 2 or 3 as factors, but that would violate the condition that a(3) = 9 needs to share a factor with three other terms.
%e A395970 a(8) = 187. Note that 187 = 11*17 so it is the first term whose larger prime factor does not equal prime(n), and hence is the first term to differ from A395795. This value can be accepted as after 187 two more terms must contain a factor of 11 to satisfy a(5) = 55, four more terms must contain a factor of 17 to satisfy a(7) = 119, while there have been two prior terms that contain 11 and 17 as factors, and as 2 + 4 + 2 = 8, the value a(8) = 187 can be satisfied.
%e A395970 a(9) = 209. Note that 209 = 11*19 and 19 has not appeared as a factor of any previous term. Any time such a prime occurs the candidate will always be accepted as the number of required subsequent appearance of that prime as a factor can be set such that the sum of the number of previous terms containing the other prime factor, the number of subsequent terms still remaining that will contain the other prime factor, and the number of subsequent terms still remaining that will contain the new prime factor equals n. In this particular case 11 has appeared as a factor in two previous terms and it must appear in one more term to satisfy a(5) = 55, so 19 must therefore appear as a factor in 9 - 2 - 1 = 6 more terms.
%Y A395970 Cf. A395795, A395360, A392373, A002808, A006881.
